Based on the assembled data and its appropriate variables, R language (R Foundation for Statistical Computing, Vienna, Austria) was used to demonstrate the trends of flood occurrences and associated deaths, injured people, total affected population and total economic damage among the 5 sub-regions of APAC. Trend polylines were generated to visualize and analyze both the inter-annual fluctuations and variations in the trends among the 5 sub-regions as well as the overall trend in APAC as a whole by using the linear regression in three phases including phase I (1990–2000), phase II (2001–2010), and phase III (2011–2018) (see Figs. 2–6




                        ). These phases represent the periods of mild, severe and extreme weather, respectively —which were decided based on the years when various weather events of different magnitudes and particularly floods occurred. Besides, extreme values that might affect the illustration of the trends were removed when generating the regression lines to help in examining their implication on the 5 targets of SDG13. On the other hand, Box and Whisker plots were used to show the distribution of flood occurrences and associated impacts namely; deaths, injured people, total affected population and total economic damage in the 10 most-affected countries based on the bottom and top quartiles, representing 25th and 75th percentiles, respectively (Fig. 7
                        ).
